#### Solution B(b) — PHP Username/Password Validation (7 marks)

**Importance of Server-Side Validation (2 marks):**

Server-side validation is the **final and most trusted layer** of input verification. The client is untrusted because users can:
- Disable JavaScript
- Modify DOM values via browser DevTools
- Send HTTP requests directly using `curl`, `Postman`, or `Burp Suite`

PHP runs on the **server** which the attacker does not control. Therefore, all critical validation (authentication, authorization, business rules) must be enforced in PHP. Skipping it opens the door to **SQL injection, XSS, buffer overflow, and privilege escalation attacks**.

**PHP Implementation (5 marks):**

```php
<?php
$user = $_POST['username'] ?? '';
$pass = $_POST['password'] ?? '';

$errors = [];

// Username: 3-20 alphanumeric
if (!preg_match('/^[a-zA-Z0-9_]{3,20}$/', $user)) {
    $errors[] = "Username must be 3-20 alphanumeric characters";
}

// Password: min 8, at least 1 upper, 1 lower, 1 digit
$passRe = '/^(?=.*[A-Z])(?=.*[a-z])(?=.*\d).{8,}$/';
if (!preg_match($passRe, $pass)) {
    $errors[] = "Password must be 8+ chars with upper, lower, and digit";
}

if (empty($errors)) {
    echo "Valid credentials accepted";
} else {
    foreach ($errors as $e) echo "- $e<br>";
}
?>
```

---

> [!WARNING]
> **KTU Examiner's Valuation Warning — Common Pitfalls**
> 1. **Forgetting `return` in `onsubmit="return validateForm()"`** — The `return` keyword is mandatory. Without it, the form will submit even if the function returns `false`. **(-2 marks)**
> 2. **Using `innerHTML =` for errors but never clearing them** — Old errors persist on subsequent submissions. Always reset the `<span>` contents at the start of validation. **(-1 mark)**
> 3. **Relying solely on JavaScript** — If your answer only shows JS validation and no PHP, the examiner will deduct up to **50% marks** because security must be server-side.
> 4. **Forgetting `htmlspecialchars()` in PHP echo** — Direct echoing of `$_POST` data is an XSS vulnerability. **(-1 mark for security awareness)**
> 5. **Wrong regex anchors** — Missing `^` and `$` allows partial matches. For example, `/^\d{10}$/` rejects `"9876543210abc"`, but `/\d{10}/` would accept it. **(-1 mark)**
> 6. **Not handling `$_POST` with `isset()` or `??`** — Triggers PHP notices in strict mode.

