## 1. Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

### 1.1 Formal Academic Definition (KTU 2024 Syllabus Terminology)

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Client-side scripting** refers to the execution of scripts (typically **JavaScript**) within the user's web browser, where the source code is downloaded, parsed, and executed by the browser engine. **Server-side scripting** refers to the execution of scripts (typically **PHP**, Python, Node.js, etc.) on the web server, where the server processes the script and returns only the resulting **HTML** output to the client's browser. **CSS (Cascading Style Sheets)** is a declarative, rule-based stylesheet language used to control the **presentation layer** (layout, color, typography, animation) of web documents.

According to the **KTU 2024 Scheme PCCNL507 syllabus**, Module Experiment 2 mandates that students *"Develop and execute Client-side and Server-side scripts using CSS, JavaScript and PHP"* — typically achieved by building a single integrated web application (such as a student registration form, login system, or dynamic calculator) that demonstrates **styling (CSS)**, **client-side validation/interactivity (JavaScript)**, and **server-side data processing (PHP)**.

### 1.2 Conceptual Analogy — "The Three Pillars of a Restaurant"

Imagine a modern restaurant:

- **HTML** is the **physical building** — the tables, chairs, doors, and walls. It is the raw *structure*.
- **CSS** is the **interior decorator** — paints the walls, arranges the lighting, sets the ambiance. It is *presentation*.
- **JavaScript (Client-side)** is the **waiter** who interacts directly with the customer at the table, takes the order, validates it (e.g., "Do you have an ID for the wine?"), and provides instant feedback. The customer can see the waiter and talk to them directly.
- **PHP (Server-side)** is the **head chef in the kitchen** — the customer never sees them. The waiter takes the order, sends it to the chef, the chef cooks the meal, and the waiter brings the finished plate back.

The customer (browser) never enters the kitchen (server); they only see the final plated dish (HTML response).

> [!NOTE]
> **Why this distinction matters in KTU exams:** Examiners frequently test the boundary between client-side and server-side execution. A common mistake students make is assuming JavaScript "writes to a database" — it cannot. It can only send an **HTTP request** to PHP, which then writes to the database.

### 1.3 Core Metrics & Standard Boundaries

| Parameter | Client-side (JS) | Server-side (PHP) |
|---|---|---|
| **Execution Location** | User's browser (V8, SpiderMonkey) | Web server (Apache, Nginx + PHP-FPM) |
| **Visibility of Code** | Source visible via "View Source" | Source hidden; only output is sent |
| **Primary Role** | Interactivity, validation, DOM manipulation | Business logic, DB access, authentication |
| **Standard Port** | N/A (runs on client) | **Port 80 (HTTP) / 443 (HTTPS)** |
| **Typical Latency** | **< 50 ms** (no network round-trip) | **50 – 500 ms** (depends on network + server) |

> [!TIP]
> KTU examiners often ask: *"Where does JavaScript execute? Where does PHP execute?"* — Memorize this two-column matrix to secure the **2-mark** "distinguish" questions.

