## 2. Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Cheat Sheet

### 2.1 The Three-Tier Architecture (Why It Exists)

The modern web operates on a strict **separation of concerns** principle, originally codified in the **W3C Web Architecture** and reinforced in the **KTU 2024 OBE framework**:

1. **Content Layer (HTML)** — Semantic structure of the page.
2. **Presentation Layer (CSS)** — Visual styling, responsive layout, animations.
3. **Behavior Layer (JavaScript)** — Client-side dynamic behavior, event handling, AJAX.
4. **Logic Layer (PHP)** — Server-side business rules, data persistence, security.

This separation exists because mixing concerns leads to **maintainability nightmares**, **security vulnerabilities** (e.g., exposing DB credentials in JS), and **incompatibility issues** across browsers.

### 2.2 CSS — Cascading Style Sheets

**Core Concept:** CSS operates on the principle of *cascading* — when multiple rules apply to an element, a strict priority order resolves conflicts.

**Priority Order (lowest → highest):**
1. Browser default styles
2. External stylesheet (low specificity)
3. Internal `<style>` block
4. Inline `style="..."` attribute
5. `!important` declaration
6. Order of appearance (later wins, for equal specificity)

**Three Methods of CSS Application:**
- **Inline:** `<p style="color:red;">` — highest specificity, hard to maintain.
- **Internal:** `<style>...</style>` in `<head>` — scoped to one page.
- **External:** `<link rel="stylesheet" href="style.css">` — best practice, reusable.

**CSS Selector Specificity (KTU High-Yield):**

$$\text{Specificity} = (a, b, c, d)$$

where:
- $a$ = number of **ID selectors** (`#id`)
- $b$ = number of **class selectors** (`.class`), attribute selectors (`[attr]`), pseudo-classes (`:hover`)
- $c$ = number of **type selectors** (`p`, `div`) and pseudo-elements (`::before`)
- $d$ = number of **universal selectors** (`*`)

A selector with specificity $(0, 1, 1, 0)$ beats $(0, 1, 0, 1)$.

### 2.3 JavaScript — Client-Side Scripting

**Core Concept:** JavaScript is an **interpreted, weakly-typed, prototype-based, multi-paradigm** scripting language standardized as **ECMAScript (ES)**. The current major versions are **ES6 (ES2015)** through **ES2024**.

**Key Constructs (KTU High-Yield):**
- **Variables:** `var` (function-scoped, hoisted), `let` (block-scoped, mutable), `const` (block-scoped, immutable binding).
- **Functions:** `function name(){}`, arrow functions `() => {}`, anonymous callbacks.
- **DOM API:** `document.getElementById()`, `document.querySelector()`, `element.addEventListener()`.
- **Events:** `onclick`, `onload`, `onmouseover`, `onsubmit`, `onchange`.
- **Form Validation:** `document.forms["myForm"]["email"].value` and `if (value === "")`.

### 2.4 PHP — Server-Side Scripting

**Core Concept:** PHP (**PHP: Hypertext Preprocessor**) is a **server-side, interpreted, weakly-typed, C-inspired** scripting language designed specifically for web development. The current stable version is **PHP 8.3** (as of KTU 2024 syllabus era).

**PHP File Handling Rules:**
- PHP files have extension **`.php`**.
- PHP code is embedded in HTML using `<?php ... ?>` tags.
- The **PHP interpreter** (Zend Engine) processes the entire file *before* sending output to the browser.
- Any text outside `<?php ... ?>` is sent to the browser **verbatim** as HTML.

**Key Superglobals (KTU High-Yield):**
- `$_GET` — Data sent via URL query string (`?name=John`).
- `$_POST` — Data sent via HTTP POST (form submission).
- `$_REQUEST` — Merged `$_GET`, `$_POST`, and `$_COOKIE`.
- `$_SERVER` — Server and execution environment info (`$_SERVER['REQUEST_METHOD']`).
- `$_SESSION` — Persists user data across multiple page requests.
- `$_COOKIE` — Small files stored on the client.
- `$_FILES` — Uploaded file metadata.

**Form Submission Methods:**
- **`method="get"`** — Data appended to URL, visible, limited length (~2048 chars), bookmarkable, **not secure**.
- **`method="post"`** — Data in HTTP body, not visible in URL, no length limit, secure for sensitive data.

### 2.5 KTU High-Yield Cheat Sheet (Reference Table)

| Concept | Symbol/Syntax | File Extension | Execution Engine | Output to Browser |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| **HTML** | `<tag>...</tag>` | `.html`, `.htm` | Browser parser | Full document |
| **CSS** | `selector { property: value; }` | `.css` | Browser CSS engine | Style rules (no output) |
| **JavaScript** | `function() { ... }` | `.js` | Browser JS engine (V8, etc.) | DOM modifications, alerts |
| **PHP** | `<?php echo ...; ?>` | `.php` | Zend Engine (server) | Pure HTML/text |

| Client-side vs Server-side Decision Rule | Use Client-side (JS) | Use Server-side (PHP) |
|---|---|---|
| **Validating email format** | ✔ Yes (instant feedback) | Possible but slow |
| **Storing user password** | ✘ NEVER (insecure) | ✔ Yes (with hashing) |
| **Showing/hiding a menu** | ✔ Yes | Overkill |
| **Querying a database** | ✘ No (DB credentials leak) | ✔ Yes |
| **Computing sales tax** | Possible | ✔ Yes (authoritative source) |

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **The "Never trust the client" principle:** In KTU viva, if asked about security, always state that **all security checks must be duplicated on the server-side** because client-side validation can be bypassed by disabling JavaScript in the browser.

