### **Question B (14 Marks) [KTU University Exam – Dec 2023, Model]**

**(a)** Explain the architecture of a PHP-based web application. How does PHP receive data from an HTML form? Illustrate with an example using both `$_GET` and `$_POST` superglobals. **(7 marks)**

**(b)** Write a complete PHP program that accepts a student's name, roll number, and three subject marks via an HTML form, calculates the **total, average, and grade**, and displays the result in a styled table. Show the HTML form, the PHP processing code, and the CSS for styling. **(7 marks)**

---

#### Model Solution to Q.B(a) — PHP Architecture & Superglobals (7 marks)

**PHP Web Application Architecture:**

```
[Browser] --HTTP Request--> [Apache Web Server] 
                                  |
                                  v
                          [PHP Interpreter]
                                  |
                                  v
                          [Script Execution]
                                  |
                                  v
                          [HTML Output Buffer]
                                  |
                                  v
[Browser] <--HTTP Response-- [Apache sends HTML]
```

**Step-by-step process:**

1. Client browser sends an HTTP request (GET/POST) to the server.
2. Apache identifies the `.php` extension and hands the file to the Zend Engine.
3. The Zend Engine executes the PHP code line by line.
4. Any output (via `echo`, `print`, or raw HTML) is buffered.
5. Once execution completes, the buffered output is sent back to the browser as a pure HTML response.
6. The browser never sees the original PHP source — only the resulting HTML.

**Receiving Form Data — `$_GET` Example:**

```html
<!-- search.html -->
<form action="search.php" method="get">
    Search: <input type="text" name="query">
    <button type="submit">Go</button>
</form>
```

```php
<!-- search.php -->
<?php
$q = htmlspecialchars($_GET['query'] ?? 'nothing');
echo "You searched for: " . $q;
?>
```
URL after submission: `http://localhost/search.php?query=hello`

**Receiving Form Data — `$_POST` Example:**

```html
<!-- login.html -->
<form action="login.php" method="post">
    User: <input type="text" name="user"><br>
    Pass: <input type="password" name="pass"><br>
    <button type="submit">Login</button>
</form>
```

```php
<!-- login.php -->
<?php
$user = htmlspecialchars($_POST['user'] ?? '');
$pass = $_POST['pass'] ?? '';

if ($user === "admin" && $pass === "1234") {
    echo "Welcome, admin!";
} else {
    echo "Invalid credentials";
}
?>
```

**Key Differences:**

| Aspect | `$_GET` | `$_POST` |
|---|---|---|
| Data location | URL query string | HTTP request body |
| Visibility | Visible in URL bar | Hidden |
| Bookmarkable | Yes | No |
| Security | Insecure for sensitive data | More secure (but use HTTPS) |
| Max length | ~2048 chars | Unlimited (server-dependent) |

